    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>CapEx Requirements:</strong> A utility has massive infrastructure requirements. Our OCF methodology does not fully penalize for these maintenance and growth capex needs.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Risk:</strong> Utilities' allowed rate of return is dictated by state commissions, meaning growth is artificially capped.</li>
    <li><strong>Interest Rates:</strong> High debt loads make utility profits highly sensitive to rising interest rates and refinancing costs.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use Operating Cash Flow instead of Free Cash Flow?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Southern Company has consistently negative or volatile FCF due to massive infrastructure projects. Standard DCFs fail with perpetual negative FCF, so OCF serves as a more reliable metric of core business cash generation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How were WACC and growth rates determined?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">We strictly derived them mathematically using multiples of the provided 10Y Treasury yield (4.18%) and actual historical financial data.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

